We need to produce JSON with fields.

Case: 45yo male, crushing chest pain, ST elevation in II, III, aVF => inferior MI. Elevated troponin, CK-MB. So primary diagnosis: Acute inferior ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI). ICD-10: I21.19 (STEMI, other acute subtypes?). Actually I21.19 is "ST elevation (STEMI) myocardial infarction involving other coronary artery". For inferior, could be I21.11 (STEMI of other sites?). Let's check: I21.0 = STEMI of anterior wall; I21.1 = STEMI of inferior wall; I21.2 = STEMI of other sites. So I21.1 is appropriate: "ST elevation (STEMI) myocardial infarction of inferior wall". Use I21.1.

Differential: Unstable angina, Non-ST elevation MI (NSTEMI), Aortic dissection, Pulmonary embolism, Pericarditis (though less likely). Provide 3-5. We'll include 4: Unstable angina (I20.0), NSTEMI (I21.4), Aortic dissection (I71.0), Pulmonary embolism (I26.99). Provide confidence levels.

Key findings: crushing substernal chest pain radiating to left arm, diaphoresis, nausea, ST elevation II,III,aVF, elevated troponin, risk factors (HTN, DM, hyperlipidemia, smoking, family hx).

Tests: immediate: 12-lead ECG (already done), cardiac biomarkers (troponin, CK-MB) (urgent), chest X-ray (routine?), bedside echocardiography (urgent), coronary angiography (immediate), CBC, BMP (routine), coagulation panel (urgent). But list tests with priority.

Management: immediate: MONA-B (morphine, oxygen if needed, nitrates, aspirin, beta-blocker, anticoagulation) plus reperfusion via primary PCI. So immediate actions: Activate cath lab, give aspirin 325 mg chew, clopidogrel 600 mg loading, give unfractionated heparin (bolus 70 U/kg), give sublingual nitroglycerin 0.4 mg q5 min x3, give high-intensity statin (atorvastatin 80 mg), consider morphine 4 mg IV if pain persists, consider beta-blocker (metoprolol 5 mg IV q5 min up to 15 mg). Also give oxygen if sat <94% (but sat 94). So not needed.

Medications: aspirin 325 mg PO chew, clopidogrel 600 mg PO loading, unfractionated heparin 70 U/kg IV bolus, nitroglycerin SL 0.4 mg q5 min PRN, metoprolol 5 mg IV bolus, high-intensity statin: atorvastatin 80 mg PO daily, possibly analgesic morphine 4 mg IV.

Consultations: Interventional cardiology: emergent, Cardiology: urgent, possibly cardiothoracic surgery if PCI fails.

Red flags: Ongoing chest pain >30 min, hypotension, arrhythmias, heart failure signs, cardiogenic shock, recurrent ischemia, contraindications to anticoagulation.

Now produce JSON.

Need confidence values: primary diagnosis high 0.96. Differentials: Unstable angina 0.6, NSTEMI 0.55, Aortic dissection 0.2, Pulmonary embolism 0.15.

